Introduction¶

This report investigates the No-Show appointment dataset, The dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil. The aim of the report is to question whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.

Dataset Description¶

. ScheduledDay: Tells us on what day the patient set up their appiontment.

. AppiontmentDay: Tells us on what day the patient is expected to show up for their appiontment.

. Gender: Indicates the sex of the patient.

. Neighborhood: Indicates the location of the hospital.

. Scholarship: Indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in the Brasilian welfare program.

. No-Show: Indicates 'Yes' for a no-show, and 'No' for a patient who showed up.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

  1. What factors influences a patient to show up or not for their scheduled appointment?

  2. Is sending an SMS as a reminder helpful to reducing the rate of No-Show?

  3. Which gender received SMS reminder the more?

# defining countplot
def count_plot(dfdata, xdata, gxlabel, gylabel, hue_order, gtitle):
    g = sns.countplot(data = dfdata, x = xdata, hue = hue_order)
    plt.title(gtitle)
    plt.xlabel(gxlabel)
    plt.ylabel(gylabel)
    return g

Research Question 2 (Is sending an SMS as a reminder helpful to reducing the rate of No-Show?)¶

In [72]:

Out[72]:

From the data displayed above, the rate of patients who received SMS is 35482, which is far below 75045 patients who didn't get an SMS.

So i discovered from the above bar chart, that patients who received SMS are more likely to showup for their Appointments, than those who didn't get a reminder.

That is, sending an SMS is kind of helpful in reducing the rate of noshow.

In [74]:

That is to say 28% of patients that booked an appointment actually got an sms as a reminder.

Conclusions¶

Q1: What factors influences a patient to show up or not for their scheduled appointments?¶

While carrying out the Exploratory Data Analysis, I discovered the findings below:

Appointments of patients on scholarship have a lower noshow rates than appointments without a scholarship.

Appointments of alcoholic patients have a higher no showup rate than non alcholic patients and i think this is due to their addictive nature.

Appointments with an Sms has a lower no showup rate than those without a reminder, i.e receiving an Sms is a factor that influences patients to showup for appointments.

Noshow rate reduces in the dataset as age decreases.

Appointments of patients with hypertension have a lower no showup rate compare to patients without the disease.

Appointments of patients with Diabetes seems to have a lower noshow up rate than those without the disease who missed their appointments.

Despite the large number of females with appointments, the males who are few has a higher showup rate compare to females who missed their appointments.

Q2: Is sending an SMS as a reminder helpful to reducing the rate of Noshows?¶

Of course yes, sending an Sms seems to be very helpful in reducing the rate of no showup.

Q3: Which gender received SMS reminder the more?¶

The female gender seems to received more sms reminder than the male but the it's just with a slight difference.

Limitations:¶

Not enough details are given about the patients as to why they didn't come.Such as:

Their emotions

Not understanding the scheduling system

And their financial status
